Headline: WSJ: US Carlyle Group To Buy 45% Of China's Xugong Group
Story: By Andrew Batson   Of THE WALL STREET JOURNAL ASIA   BEIJING (Dow Jones)--Carlyle Group has agreed to further reduce its planned stake in Xugong Group Construction Machinery Co., according to a statement from the Chinese company's listed unit, the latest twist in a long-running negotiation that has come to symbolize the difficulties foreign companies can face in making acquisitions in China.   The Washington private-equity firm Friday signed a revised agreement that calls for Carlyle to purchase 45% of the maker of cranes and earth-moving equipment, the statement said.   (This story and related background material will be available on The Wall Street Journal Web site, WSJ.com.)   In the original deal, signed in October 2005, Carlyle proposed buying a controlling 85% stake for $375 million. A year later, after failing to secure government approval, it proposed buying only 50% of the company, for about $230 million.   The new deal was announced by Xugong's listed unit, Xugong Science & Technology Co. (000425.SZ), in a statement this weekend to the Shenzhen Stock Exchange. Financial details weren't disclosed, and the arrangement is still subject to government approval.   The deal has attracted a good deal of public attention from domestic critics, who argue that China shouldn't be selling important companies to foreign investors. If the revised deal goes through, the construction-machinery company will still be 55%-owned by Xugong Group, which is itself owned by the government of the city of Xuzhou, in the eastern province of Jiangsu.   -By Andrew Batson, The Wall Street Journal Asia     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 18, 2007 04:42 ET (08:42 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UPDATE:China Minsheng Bank 06 Net Profit CNY3.83 Bln, Up 43%
Story: (Updates with more financial results for last year and financial targets for this year.)   BEIJING (Dow Jones)--Mid-sized lender China Minsheng Banking Corp. (600016.SH) said Sunday that its net profit climbed 43% last year and that it aims to realize around 38.4% net profit growth this year.   The bank posted a net profit of 3.83 billion yuan ($495.7 million) last year, up from a revised CNY2.67 billion in 2005, the bank said in a statement.   Its core revenue rose 33% on-year to CNY28.8 billion in 2006 from a revised CNY21.7 billion in 2005, the bank said.   The figures are according to Chinese accounting standards.   According to international accounting standards, Minsheng Bank's net profit was CNY3.76 billion in 2006.   China started to implement the international accounting standards from Jan. 1 this year.   Minsheng said it is aming to reach CNY5.3 billion in net profit this year. That represents a 38.4% rise from last year.   Minsheng said in its statement that its nonperforming loan ratio was 1.23% at the end of 2006, down slightly from 1.28% at the end of 2005. The target is to control its NPL ratio to no more than 2% by the end of this year, the bank said.   The bank's assets totaled CNY700.4 billion at the end of last year, up 26% from the year-earlier time, the statement said. The bank forecast its assets will reach CNY833 billion at the end of this year, representing a 18.9% growth from the year earlier.   The bank's total deposits rose 19.3% to CNY583.3 billion at the end of last year from CNY488.8 billion at the end of 2005. Total outstanding loans grew 18.4% to CNY447.4 billion from CNY378.1 billion over the same period, the bank said.   By the end of this year, the bank is aiming to grow its deposits to CNY685 billion and outstanding loans to CNY532 billion, it said.   As of Dec. 31, the bank's capital adequacy ratio was 8.12%, down from 8.26% at the end of 2005 but still above the 8% official requirement. The bank's core capital adequacy ratio stood at 4.35% at the end of last year, the statement said.   In the new year, Minsheng Bank is aiming to develop further its asset securitization business, obtain licenses for pension fund and financial futures operations, while also improving its presence in the fund management, financial leasing, and financial derivatives areas, the statement said.   Minsheng Bank, the first Chinese bank to include private companies as shareholders, has aggressively expanded its lending in recent years, putting pressure on its capital base.   It received shareholders' approval in January to set up a joint-venture fund management company with Royal Bank of Canada and Three Gorges Financial Co., a Chinese firm created to help finance the Three Gorges Dam construction project.   The bank also plans to set up a financial leasing company, the state-run Shanghai Securities News reported earlier, citing unnamed sources. The State Grid Corp. of China and a Tianjin-based company that assembles Airbus A320 planes would be Minsheng Bank's partners in the new company, the report said.     -Victoria Ruan and Rose Yu contributed to this story, Dow Jones Newswires; 8610 6588-5848; victoria.ruan@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 18, 2007 05:13 ET (09:13 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: BP Knew Of Texas Refinery Risks Before Explosion - Newspaper
Story: DOW JONES (London)--BP (BP) board directors were made aware of the link between spending cuts and poor maintenance at its Texas City refinery two-and-a-half years before the fatal explosion at the site in March 2005, the Observer newspaper reported Sunday citing an internal presentation by the company. An internal presentation made to John Manzoni, chief executive for refining and marketing, in November 2003 links the "history of reduced investment" at the Texas refinery with "poor maintenance practices," the newspaper said.   A spokesperson for BP told the Observer that previous budget decisions weren't a critical factor in the accident.   Investigators for the U.S. Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board Tuesday will publish a final report on their two-year investigation into the accident, in which 15 people were killed.   Newspaper Web site: http://observer.guardian.co.uk/     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 18, 2007 06:45 ET (10:45 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.
